Nov 10 2009 	Not ready for prime time - not now and maybe not ever.	The positive things first: friendly staff, great location. Those are really the only two redeeming things about this hotel. With so much competition in the hotel market in NYC, they are really going to have to do something drastic to compete. When we walked into our suite there was a very distinct odor of something like a damp basement. It never went away. When my husband saw the rooms he wondered what had possibly been renovated. The decor was nice enough but it didn't look that new to be honest. The bathroom was definitely new and was nicely marbled. However, for a suite it was extremely small. There was a single sink and the toilet was right next to the bathtub. The shower was decent and the fixtures were new. There is no powder room so any guests you have will be using your bathroom. The bed was very comfortable. The service was excruciatingly slow. It took over 45 minutes for a bucket of ice. It took 2 days for my husband to get internet service. The restaurant (Le Cirque) is not owned by the hotel and it took over an hour to have breakfast served. There were about 8 elevators but only 2 every working at one time. The rest were not in service. One evening we returned from dinner to find the security man and the plumber in our unit because someone on the floor above had left water running and the entire kitchenette was flooded. The did offer to move us but since we were leaving the next day, we declined. They did clean up the mess. The following morning there was non stop hammering going on below us and it took about 4 calls to the front desk to get it stopped. They are still doing construction out front so you have to walk around the barricades. We just can't ever stay here again. We're going back to either the 4 Seasons or the Mandarin where we usually stay. We thought we'd give this a try due to the renovation and the location but it's not worth the price in any way.	
Oct 31 2009 	A surprisingly poor renovation	The Pierre is a classic hotel which I have enjoyed in the past. It was indeed in need of renovation but the rooms had an old world charm. After spending US$100m on a renovation, during which the hotel was closed, I returned. What a disappointment. The rooms have lost their character, but worse there has been a lack of attention to detail. This is most obvious in the bathrooms. Two colleagues and I had exactly the same observations. One was hanging a robe next to the shower door that always got caught by the door, another putting the toilet too close to the wall, with a phone placed so close it always fell to the door. Examples of failures of detail that suggest the designer and management did not sleep repeatedly in a mock-up to analyze details of the design. Materials used are quite mediocre for a property of this standard. A colleague had a chance to talk to the manager who seemed quite defensive. Most surprising was his reaction to learning that one of his staff in the breakfast room had used his initiative to get various cooked items not on the menu from one of the kitchens. He did not praise the initiative to please a guest, but said it was against the rules and gave instruction that it should not be done the next day! I am doubtful I would stay again at the Pierre even though it is so ideally located. An unfortunate situation for the Taj group often has produced excellent hotels.	
